The error message "Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'sanitizeConfig')" typically occurs when you're trying to access the sanitizeConfig property of an object that hasn't been defined yet.

In the context of Editor.js, sanitizeConfig is a configuration object that defines which HTML tags, classes, and attributes are allowed in the output of the editor. This configuration object is usually part of the settings for each block tool.

If you're seeing this error, it likely means that one of your block tools is missing its configuration object, or the configuration object is not properly set up. Here's an example of what a properly configured block tool might look like:

consteditor=newEditorJS({tools: {header: {class: Header,config: {placeholder: 'Enter a header',levels: [1, 2, 3, 4],defaultLevel: 2,sanitizeConfig: {// This is the sanitizeConfig objectb: true, // Allow bold tagsa: {href: true}, // Allow anchor tags with href attribute// Other allowed tags, classes, and attributes go here}}},// Other tools go here}});

In this example, the header tool has a config object that includes a sanitizeConfig object. The sanitizeConfig object specifies that bold (<b>) tags and anchor (<a>) tags with the href attribute are allowed.

If you're seeing the "Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'sanitizeConfig')" error, you should check the configuration of your block tools to make sure each tool has a config object and each config object has a sanitizeConfig object.
